      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How do I calculate sludge ejection cycle time for a disc stack centrifuge?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Divide the bowl sludge space volume by the sludge generation rate (volume generated per hour). Apply a 50–70% safety factor — trigger ejections at 50–70% of theoretical full capacity to prevent sludge carryover into the disc stack. Initial cycle time is determined during commissioning by monitoring separation quality and discharge volume.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What happens if sludge ejection cycle time is set too long?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">The sludge space overfills and sludge migrates into the disc stack, causing clogging, degraded separation, and increased vibration from uneven sludge distribution. Severe overfilling requires complete bowl disassembly and manual cleaning — a 4–8 hour operation that causes unplanned production downtime.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What happens if sludge ejection cycle time is set too short?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Overly frequent ejections waste operating water, cause brief flow interruptions that disturb the liquid seal, and result in incomplete sludge discharge per cycle. Short intervals also increase wear on the ejection mechanism — operating slides, nozzles, and bowl gaskets — reducing bowl assembly service life.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What factors affect disc centrifuge sludge ejection cycle time?</h3>
            <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Key factors: sludge content of the feed liquid (higher solids = shorter interval), bowl sludge space volume, centrifuge throughput, temperature (affects sludge compaction), and sludge density. Cycle time must be re-evaluated whenever process conditions change significantly.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
